item.title: Mars Satellite Images Reveal Giant 'Kidney Beans,' Sparking Hints of Water and Life - Gadgets 360
item.description:
Mars Satellite Images Reveal Giant 'Kidney Beans,' Sparking Hints of Water and Life

Date: Not specified Source: Gadgets 360

Recent observations of frozen dunes on Mars suggest the potential presence of water and microbial life in the planet's past.

  • Frozen sand dunes observed by NASA's Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter are stationary due to carbon dioxide frost.
  • Understanding these features can help scientists determine if Mars once had conditions suitable for liquid water.
  • The Martian axial tilt may have supported a thicker atmosphere in the past, impacting its climate.
  • Research on frost patterns aids in uncovering Mars' climatic history and possible habitability.
“Studying these frost-covered dunes helps scientists assess whether liquid water was present on Mars for periods long enough to support life.”

These findings deepen our understanding of Mars' climate evolution and its implications for astrobiology.

item.title: India achieves first space docking, becoming fourth country to achieve major milestone - CNN
item.description:
India achieves first space docking, becoming fourth country to achieve major milestone

Date: December 30, 2024

Source: CNN

India made a significant leap in space exploration by becoming the fourth country to successfully execute an unmanned docking in space, marking a pivotal moment for its future missions and cementing its status as a global space power.

  • The successful docking was accomplished through the Space Docking Experiment (SpaDex), deploying two small spacecraft.
  • The spacecraft, weighing about 220 kilograms each, were launched from the Satish Dhawan Space Center.
  • Prime Minister Narendra Modi congratulated ISRO for their historic achievement, emphasizing its importance for future missions.
  • The technology developed will be essential for future endeavors such as satellite servicing and launching multiple rockets.
  • India aims to send its first astronaut to the moon by 2040 and establish its own space station by 2035.
“Spacecraft docking successfully completed! A historic moment,” the Indian Space Research Organization (ISRO) said on X.

The advancement of in-docking technology is crucial for the future of India's space missions, as it prepares to enhance its operations and capabilities on the international stage.

item.title: 20,000 Indian students landed in Canada but failed to show up at colleges last year - The Indian Express
item.description:
20,000 Indian Students in Canada Fail to Show Up at Colleges

Date: January 16, 2025

Source: The Indian Express

Indian students formed a significant portion of the nearly 50,000 international students reported as “no-shows” at Canadian colleges and universities in March and April 2024, according to Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC).

  • Almost 20,000 Indian students did not attend their designated schools.
  • The non-compliance rate for Indian students is 5.4% of the total tracked.
  • The figures were collected under the International Student Compliance Regime.
  • Non-compliance rates varied widely among students from different countries.
  • Indian authorities are investigating links between Canadian colleges and illegal migration.
  • New rules may be introduced to prevent abuse of the study permit system.
  • Discrepancies exist between Statistics Canada’s and IRCC’s data on student visa holders.
Henry Lotin, a former federal economist and immigration expert, stated that many non-compliant Indian students likely remained in Canada working while aiming for permanent residency.

The growing number of non-compliant students has raised significant concerns about the integrity of the international student system in Canada.

item.title: Air pollution before conception may increase child BMI - News-Medical.Net
item.description:
Air Pollution Before Conception Linked to Increased Child BMI

Date: 2024 | Source: Environmental Research

A study involving over 5,000 mothers reveals that exposure to air pollution prior to pregnancy is associated with higher child BMI and obesity risk factors, indicating the critical nature of preconception environmental factors.

  • Research conducted by the Keck School of Medicine of USC, Duke University, and Fudan University involving 5,834 mother-child pairs in Shanghai.
  • Significant pollutants affecting child BMI included PM2.5, PM10, and NO2.
  • Higher pollution exposure linked to a notable increase in child BMI and growth rates up to the age of two.
  • Precautions recommended for prospective parents to reduce pollution exposure, such as wearing masks and using air purifiers.
“The magnitude is small, but because air pollution is widespread and everybody is exposed, the risk of air pollution exposure on children's obesity risk may be substantial.” - Zhanghua Chen, PhD

Further research is underway to explore the direct effects of air pollution on childhood obesity and to test interventions aimed at reducing pollution exposure.

item.title: ISRO successfully docks SpaDeX satellites in space, creates history - Hindustan Times
item.description:
ISRO successfully docks SpaDeX satellites in space, creates history

Date: January 16, 2025 | Source: Hindustan Times

The Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) has successfully completed the docking process of the SpaDeX satellites, marking a significant achievement in space history.

  • The SpaDeX mission launched on December 30, 2024, from the Satish Dhawan Space Centre.
  • This makes India the fourth country to achieve successful space docking.
  • The docking was initiated using a manoeuvre from a distance of 15 meters to 3 meters.
  • The PSLV C60 rocket carried two small satellites, SDX01 (Chaser) and SDX02 (Target).
  • The SpaDeX mission is intended as a cost-effective demonstration of in-space docking technology.
"India docked its name in space history! Good Morning India ISRO’s SpaDeX mission accomplishes historic docking success. Proud to witness this moment!" - ISRO

This accomplishment is seen as a significant stepping stone for India’s future ambitious space missions, with Prime Minister Narendra Modi congratulating ISRO for their success.
